<P>
RELEASE OF 2 AMERICAN HOSTAGES BY LEBANESE SHIITE KIDNAPERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
U.S. hostage Frank Reed has been released by his Shiite Muslim kidnapers. He 
was held for approximately 3 1/2 years. 
</P>
<P>
Although happy that he has been released and is back with his family, Reed is 
reported to be angry at everybody for the length of time he and others were 
kept, and that others are still there, too (Part A, May 3). 
</P>
<P>
I wonder how he thinks the rest of us feel? He was not in Lebanon on behalf of 
the United States government. For whatever reason, and it may have been a very 
noble reason, he chose to stay in Lebanon even when it was very clear that any 
American in Lebanon ran a very high risk of being kidnaped. Finally, he was 
kidnaped. What followed cost this country, both in terms of money and in terms 
of prestige. 
</P>
<P>
Now, he is angry at everybody that he was held so long. The person he needs to 
be angry at is himself for exposing himself to that danger as he did. 
</P>
<P>
Actually, I am a little angry at him for putting us all through this affair 
when it could so easily have been avoided, and for acting as if this hostage 
matter is capable of resolution by the United States government. 
</P>
<P>
He needs to grow up. This is a dangerous world. If you take a risk, then be 
prepared to take the consequences. 
</P>
<P>
PAUL D. FILLMAN 
</P>
<P>
Long Beach 
</P>
</TEXT>
