<P>
MORNING REPORT: POP/ROCK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG BRAXTON, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Warning Sticker to Be Unveiled: A standardized advisory logo for albums 
containing explicit lyrics is scheduled to be unveiled during a news conference 
today in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
The Recording Industry Assn. of America and the National Assn. of Record 
Merchandisers will also outline a national consumer awareness campaign about 
the stickering program. The logo was developed in response to parents' 
complaints over allegedly offensive lyrics and numerous state legislative 
proposals to mandate warning stickers. An RIAA spokeswoman said Monday that 
record companies that account for 95% of all albums released in the United 
States have agreed to use the new logo. GREG BRAXTON 
