CALIFORNIA IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
SAN DIEGO; 
</P>
<P>
MEDICAL WASTE TIED TO DEFENSE DEPOT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Some of the medical equipment that washed up along a 12-mile stretch of San 
Diego County shoreline was distributed by a Department of Defense supply depot 
in Tracy in Central California, Navy officials said. But it is unclear which 
military branch may have generated the waste and who dumped it. 
</P>
<P>
The Tracy depot is the same facility identified as the source of medical debris 
that washed up on beaches in Orange and San Diego counties in 1988. The waste 
that recently drifted ashore included three injectors of atropine, used as an 
antidote to nerve gas and considered a serious public hazard. Also found were 
100 vials of penicillin and several hundred strips of anti-malaria pills. 
Health officials warned beach-goers about the injectors, which immediately 
inject atropine when placed against the skin. The drug elevates the heart rate 
and can induce delirium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
