<P>
FIRM CANCELS SMALL GROUP PLAN POLICIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Great Republic Insurance Co. announced that it is canceling health insurance 
policies sold as small group plans that serve 10,000 of its 60,000 California 
customers. Company Vice President James O'Hanlon said in Seattle that the 
decision followed discussions with California insurance regulators who 
indicated that the company had inadequate surplus reserves to support the 
amount of premiums it was collecting from its policyholders. Those canceled can 
either obtain insurance with another company or, under the law, buy a 
conversion policy that offers fewer benefits at higher premiums. 
